        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1899099948" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7077349545453763261">waffling a bit on the star rating... 3.5, if we could. not quite a 4-star read for me.<br/><br/>vaillant is a very good writer. i was riveted by his book <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9583221.The_Tiger_A_True_Story_of_Vengeance_and_Survival' title='The Tiger A True Story of Vengeance and Survival by John Vaillant' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Tiger: A True Story of Vengeance and Survival</a>, so was keen when <i>the golden spruce</i> was chosen for my in-person book group. the book club discussion was very good, and the group was divided on hadwin&apos;s fate - a testament to vaillant&apos;s writing and the structure of the book, leaving readers open to form their own ideas and opinions. <br/><br/>there is a lot of inf</span>
  <span id="freeText7077349545453763261" style="display:none">waffling a bit on the star rating... 3.5, if we could. not quite a 4-star read for me.<br /><br />vaillant is a very good writer. i was riveted by his book <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9583221.The_Tiger_A_True_Story_of_Vengeance_and_Survival" title="The Tiger A True Story of Vengeance and Survival by John Vaillant" rel="nofollow noopener">The Tiger: A True Story of Vengeance and Survival</a>, so was keen when <i>the golden spruce</i> was chosen for my in-person book group. the book club discussion was very good, and the group was divided on hadwin's fate - a testament to vaillant's writing and the structure of the book, leaving readers open to form their own ideas and opinions. <br /><br />there is a lot of information and history presented and so much of it was fascinating. there were three main issues that kept niggling at me as i read, and kept me from giving the book a higher rating: <br /><br />* wondering how this story would have been told through an indigenous author's voice and perspective;<br />* feeling distracted at moments when inferences or suppositions were made;<br />* concerns around the portrayal of hadwin's mental health/wellbeing.<br /><br />these points aside, the story is very engaging - though i wasn't quite as riveted as with <i>the tiger</i>. vaillant really does have a way of creating nonfiction page-turners, and he made me truly care about so many aspects of this story.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7077349545453763261" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
